episodes.description:
A 17-year-old Mormon girl in Oakland called the police in 1928 and said the maid had killed the baby.

When officers arrived, she smiled, introduced herself as Erna Janoschek, and told them she was the maid.

The Erna Janoschek case is disturbing on its face. Underneath it, there’s a deeper story about family abandonment, religious obsession, early psychiatric limits, and a system that could call it “duty” while families were left to deal with the fallout.

In this episode of Postmormon Postmortem, Hannah walks Jess through the case of Erna Janoschek, the 17-year-old live-in nanny who killed baby Thais Dianne Liliencrantz, and the Mormon family system surrounding her.

What we cover in this episode:
The 1928 Oakland murder of Thais Dianne Liliencrantz by 17-year-old Erna Janoschek;
Edward Janoschek’s conversion in Germany, repeated LDS mission service, and loyalty to the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints;
His 1904 letter asking the First Presidency for permission to marry before another mission, and the handwritten response granting him “one year together”;
His public criticism of church financial dealings around Temple Square, his excommunication, and what followed;
The warning signs before the murder, withdrawal, depression, mood changes, and a mental health crisis forming in plain sight;
Erna’s live-in nanny job in the Liliencrantz home, and the dynamics inside that household;
Erna’s jailhouse account of the 48 hours before the murder: dishes, exhaustion, resentment, pride, and pressure;
Erna’s writing style, her intelligence, theatricality, and the way she narrates the murder almost as literature;
The murder itself, including her decision to choose “the one I loved” because it felt “more dramatic”;
Police interrogation, newspaper coverage, and her laughter and courtroom behavior;
Her refusal to be called insane, and the insanity plea entered by her public defender;
Psychiatric testimony in 1928, including early arguments for intervention before violence;
The legal gap between being deeply unwell and being considered legally sane;
The trial, guilty verdict, and Judge Wood’s life sentence;
San Quentin, her later diagnosis, and transfer to a California state mental hospital;
Parole, name change, and the reality that she went on to live a long life;
Why this case lands differently when you look at Mormon family systems, priesthood duty, and intergenerational damage.

